As shown in Fig. 1, the CNDs are uniform nanoparticles with average diameter of about 8.08 nm (G-CNDs), 3.42 nm (Y-CNDs), and 2.86 nm (R-CNDs), and the size effect is not directly related to redshift of Y-CNDs and R-CNDs here. The Raman spectra presented two significantly bands at crystalline G band (∼1550 cm−1) and disordered D band (∼1350 cm−1) (
                           Fig. S1
                        ). The peak area ratios of D and G bands after fitting are 2, 0.28, 3.76, respectively. The low value of Y-CNDs hints the high degree of graphitization. Thus, particle size and graphitization degree may not be the main causes of redshift of R-CNDs.

As shown in X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) spectra ( Fig. S2
), an obviously increase in content of O and N of Y-CNDs shows that FeCl3 is conducive to catalyzed-oxidative polymerize during the carbonization reaction of oPD. In the C 1 s spectra (Fig. 3
a, d, g), the Y-CNDs have graphite carbon (283.93 eV) that is consistent with the results of Raman. The increase on graphitization of carbon of Y-CNDs does lead to a certain redshift (32 nm). In the N 1 s spectra (Fig. 3 b, e, h), the relative contents of pyrrolic-N and amino-N in R-CNDs increase. However, considering low total nitrogen content in R-CNDs, the influence of pyrrolic-N and amino-N on the red-shift is excluded [16]. Moreover, the signals of Fourier transform infrared (FT-IR) spectroscopy are classified as shown in Fig. S3 , implying the formation of polyaromatic structures in the CNDs cores and rich surface groups. Especially for R-CNDs, the stretching vibration of –OH and –NH decreases, stretching vibration of C = O/C = C increases shows that the surface oxidation degree improved and the surface functional groups enriched, which plays an important role in the FL emission regulation.
